	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				The Shaman<BR>
<BR>
The shaman is a great class, which offers a tons role-play opportunity in EverQuest.   First, they are only for the &#8220;Large&#8221; races (Barbarians, Trolls, and Ogres).  You are the Wise one in the midst of mindless warriors, eager for the slaughter.  You are responsible for guiding your brethren, because you are wise.  Being of a big race gives you a nice advantage when first starting out, as you will have an easier time gaining your first few levels.  Second, you&#8217;re probably going to be rare.  Most people who play the big races want to be the strong warrior or shadowknight.  They will probably wonder why you&#8217;re a shaman as they go stomping about the newbie grounds killing everything in sight.  When they die again and again from levels 5 up, they start to shout:  &#8220;Looking for shaman level 6-8!&#8221;,  &#8220;Can anybody heal me?&#8221;, &#8220;Can someone plz cure my plague rat disease?&#8221;  <BR>
<BR>
Once they have partied with a shaman, they will always want a shaman.  Here&#8217;s why.  You can buff.  Shaman buffs are the second best in the game (behind Enchanters) but you have more buffs to choose from.  Virtually every physical attribute (like Strength, Agility, Dexterity) can be raised through your buff spells.  You can heal.  This dramatically reduces time warriors spend sitting on their butts.  You can draw enemies.  Although shaman damage spells are pretty weak, they will get a monster&#8217;s attention and draw him to your party.  If a warrior wants to do this, he has to run up to the monster and start attacking it.  You&#8217;ll see lots of guys chasing down mobs, too, when a few of your spells can finish it off.  Eventually shamans get nice DOT (damage over time) spells.<BR>
<BR>
The starting shaman<BR>
<BR>
When distributing your starting ability points, your race is fairly important.  I suggest putting a few points into agility and the rest into Wisdom.  Wisdom directly affects your mana.  And if you are playing well, you will need as much mana as possible.  You are a big race and will start out stronger than most warriors in the game.  Don&#8217;t put any in Stamina for the same reason.  The rest of your stats are not bad.  Don&#8217;t waste any on Charisma.  You might consider a few in Int to help with skill learning, but I wouldn&#8217;t even do that.  Focus on 1. Wis 2. Agility.  Not being hit is often more important than hitting for a few extra points of damage.<BR>
<BR>
You start out with 2 spells (Inner fire and Minor healing) in addition to a newbie club and food, water, guild note, and your PK book.  Be sure to scribe these spells into your spell book before you do anything else.  The reason is that if you die without having scribed those spells you lose them.  Poof.  Don&#8217;t do that.  <BR>
<BR>
After giving the note to your guildmaster, train 5 points in 1 &#8211;Handed Blunt, memorize the two spells and head out to your local newbie area.  I have played both a Troll and a Barbarian shaman, and think that Barbarians have a little easier time starting out, mainly because there are more players around to help you out.  Also, the Barbarians have merchants in the newbie zone, so you don&#8217;t have to go very far to resupply or sell your goods.<BR>
<BR>
Tactics<BR>
Cast Inner fire on yourself, this will give you a few extra hit points and an armor class bonus.  Make Slam a hot key.  It usually won&#8217;t do much damage, but then again, most newbie creatures can&#8217;t take a lot of damage.  Many shaman forget that as a big race, you start with the Slam skill.  Use it!  At first you&#8217;ll be running up to monsters and attacking them.  Keep bashing until it is dead.  As soon as you&#8217;ve saved up some money (around 1.5 gold or so) immediately go back to town to buy Burst of Flame spell.  Memorize this spell and head back out.  I usually have both the healing spell and the Burst of Flame spell on hot keys.<BR>
<BR>
With burst of flame you become much better at killing things.  Use it first on a monster to get its attention.  It will only do about 4 damage, but the monster will run right up to you.  No chasing it down like a grunt warrior.  You can pick your battles.  (If you see a warrior trying to run up and attack a creature, don&#8217;t steal it from him, even though you can.  This is rude.)  Your main priority is decaying skeletons with weapons.  Always always always attack decaying skeletons with weapons.  You will make more money that way than any other as a newbie, and you stand a good chance of getting a weapon you can use.<BR>
<BR>
Level 2<BR>
When you hit level 2, life becomes a little easier.  Save your practice/training points.  You don&#8217;t need to use them yet.  You have more mana, more hit points, and more money.  Your next goal is to get money to buy 2 more spells:  Strengthen and Dextrous Aura.  These are buff spells and they make you even with Warriors in terms of battle.  With Strengthen, Dextrous Aura and Inner Fire, you should be able to safely handle anything in the newbie zones except multiple monsters.  There are exceptions to this (Trolls have to face a Fungus tracker which tends to spawn right at the beginning of the zone.)  Don&#8217;t waste money on Endure cold.  No one is attacking you with cold attacks just yet.  Flash of Light can help in a tight situation, but it&#8217;s better to just use Burst of Flame.  Practice using it in between monster attacks while fighting.  Before you know it, you&#8217;ll be level 3.<BR>
<BR>
Level 3 <BR>
At this point you&#8217;re even stronger and the newbie monsters won&#8217;t even be a challenge.  Be sure to save all of those Bear pelts for level 3.  When you hit level 3, go back to your guild and train 10 practice points (you did save them didn&#8217;t you?) into Tailoring.  Trust me on this one.  You should also have enough money for a tailoring kit and the &#8220;How to Sew&#8221; book or pamphlet.   Now you can make your own patchwork armor from the bear pelts.  Don&#8217;t even bother with buying any armor yet.  Just use those pelts and buy a pattern and put them in the sewing kit.   You might fail a few times.  I had 6 pelts to practice with and was successful 4 out of the 6 times.  One of the failures actually raised my skill 1 point to 11.  Now you want to keep fighting bear cubs and even buying pelts from other players until you have a full set of patchwork.  As a Troll shaman you should always be on the lookout for Froglok tads which can carry pieces of netted armor.<BR>
<BR>
Future levels<BR>
The first spell to buy at level 5 is Create water.  This will save you and your party much money over time.  You can even store created water in the bank and retrieve it.  The second spell to buy is Feet like Cat.  This is an agility buff spell, and makes you harder to hit.  If you are low on mana, use this buff spell first, because agility directly affects how often you are hit.  Trust me.  This is more important than strength of dexterity.  Other useful spells are Drowsy (a debuffing spell which slows a monster&#8217;s attacks) and Fleeting Fury which is like a temporary boost to your stats.  All of the spells at this level are useful, and I would buy that Endure cold spell you skipped on earlier too.  You can make some money by making patchwork for other players, but most you will get from adventuring.  Money will always be tight like any spellcaster, but your situation is a little worse than most, because you also have armor and weapons to worry about.  Get the spells first and armor second.  At this point you will know how to play your character as well as anyone.<BR>
<BR>
General tips<BR>
At low levels you can fight as well as a tank and help speed the recovery process with healing spells.  Your main strength will be in Buffing other players and keeping them alive to fight for you.  You can go in and bash with the best of them, but your main priority is keeping them alive, by healing and making them stronger.  Be friendly to those around you.  Cast buff spells on people you don&#8217;t know and always heal someone if they are about to die.  Warriors may laugh until you save their butt, and then you will have their respect forever.  Later in life, you might want to find a Monk to team up with.  Your buffing spells will make that character a Mega tank.   Clerics and Shaman start out similar in that they are like a hybrid class, fighting and casting.  But Shaman will always be better at melee, because of your naturally high race stats.  When you factor in your buff spells, Shaman can almost go solo through the entire game.<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
	<tr>
			<td nowrap bgcolor="#808080" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_silver.gif">	
